# Desktop launcher

Click an icon in `~/Applications/App It/` (or its Dock Stack) to launch.

## First launch

1. Right-click the app icon and choose **Open**, then click **Open** in the dialog. macOS remembers and skips this on subsequent launches (Gatekeeper, unsigned bundle).
2. The first cold start takes 5–15 s while the dev server compiles. URL-only apps (for example, Claude Artifact wrappers) do not compile locally; first launch is WebKit startup plus sign-in/network time.
3. If a "couldn't be opened" alert appears citing the dev server, open `~/Library/Logs/app-it/<slug>/server.log`. The alert quotes the tail; the full log usually shows the cause.

## Apps

- **__APP_NAME__** (`__APP_NAME__.app`) — __<one-line description, e.g. "the runtime demo on :__PORT__">__
- **__APP_NAME_2__** (`__APP_NAME_2__.app`) — __<one-line description>__   *(if multi-app)*

Each `.app` runs as a real macOS app with its own Dock icon and its own window — **not** a Chrome `--app` window. The `.app` embeds a small Swift WebKit shell so the Dock icon stays ours and macOS handles single-instance activation natively.

## Launch behavior

The launcher is **persistent** — designed for daily use, not single-shot demos.

- **First click after boot:** 5–15 s for the dev server cold start.
- **Closing the window with the red X does NOT kill the dev server.** It stays warm. Click the icon again and the window opens within ~250 ms.
- **Cmd+Q (or right-click → Quit in the Dock) DOES kill the server.** Full-shutdown path — use when you actually want everything to stop.
- **Re-clicking the icon while the window is open** brings the existing window forward. No second window.
- **Sibling appified apps coexist by default.** With `port_mode: "fallback"`, if another `.app` already grabbed the configured port, this launcher scans upward and picks a free port. With `port_mode: "fixed"`, the configured port is required and a busy port fails clearly so browser storage stays on one origin. The runtime port is recorded at `~/Library/Application Support/app-it/<slug>/server.port`.
- **Claude Artifact wrappers.** Sharing the `.app` shares only the hosted URL wrapper, not Claude credentials. Each recipient signs into Claude and uses their own plan.

To stop the persistent dev servers from the terminal:

```bash
./scripts/desktop-quit.sh
```

Reboot also works.

## Install / update

```bash
./scripts/desktop-build.sh    # rebuild .app bundle(s) under desktop/
./scripts/desktop-install.sh  # copy them into ~/Applications/App It/, refresh Dock
```

The `~/Applications/App It/` folder is meant to live as a Dock Stack — drag it to the right side of the Dock once and every appified app shows up there automatically.

## Replace an app icon

Replace the source PNG (square, ≥ 1024×1024 ideal):

- __APP_NAME__: `assets/__APP_SLUG__-icon.png`

Check how it will actually look in the Dock *before* rebuilding (optional but recommended):

```bash
APP_NAME='__APP_NAME__' APP_SLUG='__APP_SLUG__' ./scripts/desktop-icons-preview.sh --open
```

This renders the icon at every Dock/Finder size on light and dark backgrounds and flags
common problems in plain language (wordmark that smears at 16px, low contrast, too much
transparent padding, sub-1024 source). Deterministic and local — nothing leaves your machine.

Then:

```bash
./scripts/desktop-build.sh    # mtime-aware: regenerates icns automatically
./scripts/desktop-install.sh  # icon-hash gated: refreshes Dock when bytes changed
```

If the Dock briefly shows a stale thumbnail after a reboot, drag the Stack out and back in to force-rebuild — the install step's automatic Dock refresh covers everything else.

## Something's wrong? Diagnose it

```bash
./scripts/desktop-doctor.sh          # read-only health check for one launcher
./scripts/desktop-doctor.sh --tail   # …and show the tail of the launcher log
./scripts/desktop-doctor.sh --json   # machine-readable checks, counts, and ports
./scripts/desktop-verify.sh          # headless smoke + doctor summary
./scripts/desktop-verify.sh --json   # machine-readable verification summary
```

It checks the things that actually break a generated app — config, the installed
`.app`, icon, bundle id, signature, quarantine, the preferred-vs-runtime port,
stale processes, whether the running server really belongs to this launcher, and
whether the installed launcher predates the current templates — and prints a
short report you can paste straight into a bug report. It never touches your
project; when it isn't sure, it says "probably".

To clean up app-it's **own** generated state (stale pid/port files, a stale
LaunchServices entry, a rebuilt icon, quarantine on the `.app`):

```bash
./scripts/desktop-doctor.sh --fix-safe
```

`--fix-safe` only ever touches app-it's generated artifacts — never your source,
dependencies, or config. For multi-app projects, pass a slug to pick one:
`./scripts/desktop-doctor.sh <slug>`.

For automation, `./scripts/desktop-doctor.sh --json <slug>` emits valid JSON
with selected app metadata, preferred/runtime ports, counts, and per-check
records. `./scripts/desktop-verify.sh --json <slug>` wraps the behavior-first
headless path: built/installed bundle status, APP_IT_SMOKE runtime launch,
HTTP response, doctor summary, and manual labels for window/red-X/Cmd+Q checks
that need a visible macOS session. Add `--strict` when warnings or failures
should make the command fail.

## Logs & runtime files

Per app, logs live under `~/Library/Logs/app-it/<slug>/`:
- `server.log` — dev-server output. If startup fails, an alert quotes the tail.
- `backend.log` — *(multi-server only)* backend service output.

Per app, runtime state lives under `~/Library/Application Support/app-it/<slug>/`:
- `server.port` — the actual runtime port (may differ from the configured port only when `port_mode: "fallback"` kicked in).
- `server.pid` — supervisor PID. The launcher's reattach gate walks this PID's descendant tree, so warm re-launch works for `pnpm`/`npm`/`yarn`/`bun`/`concurrently` chains.
- `server.identity` — PID start-time proof, so stale or reused PID files are cleaned without stopping unrelated processes.
- `backend.port`, `backend.pid`, `backend.identity` — *(multi-server only)* backend service equivalents.
- `runtime.json` — *(multi-server only)* compact frontend/backend preferred-vs-runtime port summary for doctor/verify and automation.

## Architecture

```
desktop/<App Name>.app/
  Contents/
    Info.plist                       # CFBundleExecutable = "run"
    MacOS/
      run                            # tiny native Mach-O stub (execs run.sh)
      run.sh                         # bash launcher (server boot + exec wrapper)
      wrapper                        # compiled Swift WebKit shell (universal)
    Resources/
      AppIcon.icns                   # generated from assets/<slug>-icon.png
```

`PROJECT_ROOT` is **baked at build time** so the bundle keeps working after it's copied to `~/Applications/App It/`. Re-run `./scripts/desktop-build.sh` if the repo ever moves. Worktree builds bake the worktree path — re-run from the canonical repo location after the worktree merges.

## Known limitations

- **Unsigned bundles.** First launch triggers Gatekeeper. Right-click → Open once and macOS remembers.
- **Repo path is baked in.** Moving the repo means re-running `./scripts/desktop-build.sh && ./scripts/desktop-install.sh`.
- **Persistent server.** Closing the window leaves the dev server running. That's intentional — it's why the second launch is fast — but it means `lsof -i :<port>` keeps showing bindings until you Cmd+Q the app, run `desktop-quit.sh`, or reboot.
- **WebKit, not Chromium.** If you need Chrome devtools or a Chromium-only feature, point a regular browser tab at the runtime URL.
- **Distribution to other users not supported.** Unsigned, no notarization, no auto-update. Your other Mac counts (universal arm64+x86_64 binary), but a colleague needs to right-click → Open the first time too.
